   By Jack McCarthy, Special to the Tribune

   7:37 p.m. CDT, September 14, 2013

   NASCAR brass laid down the law with team owners, crews and drivers on
   what is and is not acceptable behavior during a meeting Saturday at
   Chicagoland Speedway.

   After a week filled with penalties and unprecedented changes to the
   Chase for the Sprint Cup field, officials outlined policy and technical
   changes to take effect with Sunday's Geico 400 race.

   NASCAR President Mike Helton offered a broad summary during a news
   conference preceding Saturday's Dollar General 300 Nationwide Series
   race.

   "Any competitor who takes action with the intent to artificially alter
   the finishing positions of the event or encourages, persuades or
   induces others to artificially alter the finishing positions of the
   event shall be subject to a penalty from NASCAR," said Helton, quoting
   from a new rule effective immediately.

   Trades for favors or track position, intentionally causing a caution or
   a wreck or intentionally pitting to gain favor are among unacceptable
   actions Helton offered as examples.

   "It's good to clarify what we can and can not do," said Joey Logano,
   the pole sitter for Sunday's Chase race. "We're all competitors and
   we're going to try to gain a competitive advantage where we can. Any
   time you can clarify the rules in helps our sport."

   Specific changes were contained in a technical bulletin issued later
   Saturday.

   "Everyone should have a pretty clear understanding of (what the line
   is)," Paul Wolfe, crew chief for driver Brad Keselowski. "If you go out
   there and run 100 percent to your ability and run a normal race then
   everything will be fine."

   Changes came in the wake of a controversial finish to last Saturday's
   regular-season finale at Richmond that led to the removal of Martin
   Truex Jr. from the Chase field and the addition of Ryan Newman and Jeff
   Gordon.

   NASCAR also issued a series of suspensions and fines while two
   ownership groups were placed on probation.

   2-for-2: Kyle Busch won his second race in less than 24 hours at
   Chicagoland, starting at the pole and leading all but five laps of
   Saturday's Nationwide Dollar General 300.

   The victory was his 10th of the season and seventh from the pole in 20
   Nationwide runs. The 195 laps broke Dale Earnhardt Sr.'s Nationwide
   record on a 1.5-mile track set in 1986 at Charlotte Motor Speedway.

   "This was an awesome race car," said Busch, who claimed his third
   career triumph at Chicagoland Speedway. "My car had a lot of grip in
   it. I could just do anything I wanted to. I could go in any grove I
   wanted to."

   Logano was runner up, 1.615 seconds behind Busch.

   "That 54 car (Busch's) was so much faster," he said. "I don't think he
   ran a hard lap the whole race. He had a superior car and we have to go
   back and see how we can get our car faster."

   Sam Hornish Jr. was third and maintained his Nationwide Series lead by
   17 points over Austin Dillon.

   On Friday, Busch held off Keselowski to win the Camping World Trucks
   series EnjoyIllinois.com 225. Busch goes for a three-race sweep in
   Sunday's Geico 400.

   Wary of weather: Chicagoland officials are keeping a watch on radar,
   hoping potential rain stays away from Joliet and Sunday's Chase for the
   Sprint Cup kickoff race. Forecasts call for scattered showers that
   could delay the Geico 400, set for approximately 1 p.m.

   "We'll do everything we can do get the race in," Chicagoland chief
   Scott Paddock said.

   The worst case scenario occurred in 2011 when storms pushed
   Chicagoland's Sprint Cup debut race from Sunday to Monday.

